This paper is about attacking black-box neural networks using a novel framework that combines an autoencoder with a zeroth-order optimization method. The paper focuses on image classifiers trained by deep neural networks, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) or Machine Learning (cs.LG) categories. The paper also discusses adversarial examples and model robustness, which are topics commonly studied in the Computer Security and Cryptography (cs.CR) category. Additionally, the paper proposes an adaptive random gradient estimation strategy and an autoencoder for attack acceleration, which are techniques that fall under the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) categories. Therefore, the most likely categories for this paper are cs.LG and cs.CV, followed by cs.CR, cs.AI, and cs.NE.
